13 SECTION 5. G.S. 47C-3-107.1 reads as rewritten:
14 "§ 47C-3-107.1. Procedures for fines and suspension of condominium privileges or services.
15 Unless a specific procedure for the imposition of fines or suspension of condominium
16 privileges or services is provided for in the declaration, a hearing shall be held before the
17 executive board or an adjudicatory panel appointed by the executive board to determine if any
18 unit owner should be fined or if condominium privileges or services should be suspended
19 pursuant to the powers granted to the association in G.S. 47C-3-102(11). Any adjudicatory panel
20 appointed by the executive board shall be composed of members of the association who are not
21 officers of the association or members of the executive board. The unit owner charged shall be
22 given notice of the charge, opportunity to be heard and to present evidence, and notice of the
23 decision. A written notice of hearing shall be sent to the unit owner as provided in
24 G.S. 47C-3-116(e)(3) not less than 10 days prior to the scheduled hearing date. The notice of
25 hearing shall specify the date, time, and place of the hearing and shall include a general
26 description of each alleged violation and the action, if any, to cure each alleged violation. The
27 unit owner shall be given an opportunity to be heard and to present evidence at the hearing. A
28 written notice of the decision specifying each violation verified by the evidence and the action,
29 if any, to cure each verified violation shall be sent to the unit owner as provided in
30 G.S. 47C-3-116(e)(3). If it is decided that a fine should be imposed, a fine not to exceed one
31 hundred dollars ($100.00) may be imposed for the violation and without further hearing, for each
32 day more than five days after the decision that the violation occurs. occurs, up to a maximum
33 fine of two thousand five hundred dollars ($2,500). Such fines shall be assessments secured by
34 liens under G.S. 47C-3-116. If it is decided that a suspension of condominium privileges or
35 services should be imposed, the suspension may be continued without further hearing until the
36 violation or delinquency is cured. A unit owner may appeal a decision of an adjudicatory panel
37 to the full executive board by delivering written notice of appeal to the executive board within
38 15 days after the date of the decision. The executive board may affirm, vacate, or modify the
39 prior decision of the adjudicatory body. All fines collected pursuant to this section shall be
40 remitted to the Civil Penalty and Forfeiture Fund."
41 SECTION 6. G.S. 47C-3-116 reads as rewritten:
42 "§ 47C-3-116. Lien for sums due the association; enforcement.
43 (a) Any assessment attributable to a unit which remains unpaid for a period of 30 days or
44 longer shall constitute a lien on that unit when a claim of lien is filed of record in the office of
45 the clerk of superior court of the county in which the unit is located in the manner provided in
46 this section. A claim of lien securing a debt consisting of fines or fine-related charges shall be
47 filed separately from a claim of lien securing other sums owed to the association and shall be
48 filed within 90 days after the date the fine was imposed. As used in this section, "fines or
49 fine-related charges" means fines imposed by the association, interest on unpaid fines, or
50 attorneys' fees incurred by the association related to fines imposed by the association. Once filed,
51 a claim of lien secures all sums due the association through the date filed and any sums due to
