22 SECTION 13.(a) G.S. 7A-38.3F reads as rewritten:
23 "§ 7A-38.3F. Prelitigation mediation of condominium and homeowners owners' association
24 disputes.
25 (a) Definitions. – The following definitions apply in this section:
26 (1) Association. – An association of unit or lot owners organized as allowed under
27 North Carolina law, including G.S. 47C-3-101 and G.S. 47F-3-101.
28 (2) Dispute. – Any matter relating to real estate under the jurisdiction of an
29 association about which the member and association cannot agree. The term
30 "dispute" does not include matters expressly exempted in subsection (b) of
31 this section.
32 (3) Executive board. – The body, regardless of name, designated in the
33 declaration to act on behalf of an association.
34 (4) Mediator. – A neutral person who acts to encourage and facilitate a resolution
35 of a dispute between an association and a member.
36 (5) Member. – A person who is a member of an association of unit or lot owners
37 organized as allowed under North Carolina law, including G.S. 47C-3-101
38 and G.S. 47F-3-101.
39 (6) Party or parties. – An association or member who is involved in a dispute, as
40 that term is defined in subdivision (2) of this subsection.
41 (a1) Disputes related solely to a member's failure to timely pay an association assessment
42 or any fines or fees associated with the levying or collection of an association assessment are not
43 covered under this section.
44 (b) Voluntary Prelitigation Mediation. – Prior to filing a civil action, the The parties to a
45 dispute arising under Chapter 47C of the General Statutes (North Carolina Condominium Act),
46 Chapter 47F of the General Statutes (North Carolina Planned Community Act), or an
47 association's declaration, bylaws, or rules and regulations are encouraged to initiate mediation
48 pursuant to this section. However, disputes related solely to a member's failure to timely pay an
49 association assessment or any fines or fees associated with the levying or collection of an
50 association assessment are not covered under this section.may agree at any time to mediation of
51 the dispute pursuant to this section.
Page 16 House Bill 444-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (b1) Mandatory Prelitigation Mediation. – Prior to filing a civil action arising under
2 Chapter 47C of the General Statutes (North Carolina Condominium Act), Chapter 47F of the
3 General Statutes (North Carolina Planned Community Act), or an association's declaration,
4 bylaws, or rules and regulations, a party shall initiate mediation pursuant to this section. If an
5 action is initiated, it shall, upon the motion of any party prior to trial, be dismissed without
6 prejudice by the court unless any one or more of the following apply:
7 (1) The nonmoving party has satisfied the requirements of this section, and this
8 fact is indicated in the mediator's certification issued under subsection (g) of
9 this section.
10 (2) The court finds that a mediator failed to issue a mediator's certification under
11 subsection (g) of this section indicating that the nonmoving party satisfied the
12 requirements of this section.
13 (3) The court finds good cause for a failure to attempt mediation. Good cause
14 includes a determination that the time delay required for mediation would
15 likely result in irreparable harm or that injunctive relief is otherwise
16 warranted.
17 (c) Initiation of Mediation. – Either an association or a member may contact the North
18 Carolina Dispute Resolution Commission or the Mediation Network of North Carolina for the
19 name of a mediator or community mediation center. Upon contacting a mediator, either the
20 association or member may supply to the mediator the physical address of the other party, or the
21 party's representative, and the party's telephone number and e-mail address, if known. The
22 mediator shall contact the party, or the party's representative, to notify him or her the party of the
23 request to mediate. If the parties agree to mediate, they Unless the mediation is waived pursuant
24 to subsection (e) of this section, the parties shall request in writing that the mediator schedule the
25 mediation. The mediator shall then notify the parties in writing of the date, time, and location of
26 the mediation, which shall be scheduled not later than 25 days after the mediator receives the
27 written request from the parties.
28 (d) Mediation Procedure. – The following procedures shall apply to mediation under this
29 section:
30 (1) Attendance. – The mediator shall determine who may attend mediation. The
31 mediator may require the executive board or a large group of members to
32 designate one or more persons to serve as their representatives in the
33 mediation.
34 (2) All parties are expected to attend mediation. The mediator may allow a party
35 to participate in mediation by telephone or other electronic means if the
36 mediator determines that the party has a compelling reason to do so.
37 (3) If the parties cannot reach a final agreement in mediation because to do so
38 would require the approval of the full executive board or the approval of a
39 majority or some other percentage of the members of the association, the
40 mediator may recess the mediation meeting to allow the executive board or
41 members to review and vote on the agreement.
42 (e) Decline Mediation. – Either party to a dispute may decline mediation under this
43 section. If either party declines mediation after mediation has been initiated under subsection (c)
44 of this section but mediation has not been held, the party declining mediation shall inform the
45 mediator and the other party in writing of his or her decision to decline mediation. No costs shall
46 be assessed to any party if either party declines mediation prior to the occurrence of an initial
47 mediation meeting.Waiver of Mediation. – The parties to a dispute may agree to waive mediation
48 required by this section by informing the mediator of the waiver in writing.
49 (f) Costs of Mediation. – The costs of mediation, including the mediator's fees, shall be
50 shared equally by the parties unless otherwise agreed to by the parties. Fees shall be due and
51 payable at the end of each mediation meeting. A mediator may charge a reasonable fee, as
House Bill 444-First Edition Page 17

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 applicable, to prepare a mediator's certification required under subsection (g) of this section when
2 parties to a dispute agree to waive mediation pursuant to subsection (e) of this section or when
3 one or more parties failed or refused without good cause to attend the mediation meetings or
4 otherwise participate in the mediation. When an attorney represents a party to the mediation, that
5 party shall pay his or her the attorneys' fees.
6 (g) Certification That Mediation Concluded. – Upon a waiver of the mediation under
7 subsection (e) of this section or upon the conclusion of mediation, the mediator shall prepare a
8 certification stating the date on which the mediation was concluded and a statement of the general
9 results of the mediation, including, as applicable, that the parties waived the mediation, that an
10 agreement was reached or reached, that mediation was attempted but an agreement was not
11 reached. reached, or that one or more parties failed or refused without good cause to attend the
12 mediation meetings or otherwise participate in the mediation. If both parties participate in
13 mediation and a cause of action involving the dispute mediated is later filed, either party may file
14 the certificate with the clerk of court, and the parties shall not be required to mediate again under
15 any provision of law. The Supreme Court may adopt additional rules and standards to implement
16 this section, including an exemption from the provisions of G.S. 7A-38.1 for cases in which
17 mediation was attempted under this section. The sanctions in G.S. 7A-38.1(g) do not apply to
18 prelitigation mediation conducted under this section.
19 …
20 (j) Association Duty to Notify. – Each association shall, in writing, shall notify the
21 members of the association each year annually in writing that they may initiate mediation under
22 this section to try to resolve a dispute with the association. The association shall publish the
23 notice required in this subsection on the association's Web site; but if the association does not
24 have a Web site, the association website, or it shall publish the notice at the same time and in the
25 same manner as the names and addresses of all officers and board members of the association
26 are published as provided in G.S. 47C-3-103 and G.S. 47F-3-103."
27 SECTION 13.(b) This section becomes effective October 1, 2025, and applies to
28 actions filed on or after that date.
29 SECTION 14.(a) Article 1 of Chapter 114 of the General Statutes is amended by
30 adding a new section to read:
31 "§ 114-8.8. Collection and report of owners' association complaint data.
32 (a) The Department of Justice shall receive and record data from all complaints
33 concerning disputes between associations of unit owners or lot owners and their members as
34 required by this section. The Department of Justice shall publish a complaint form providing for
35 electronic submission of those complaints on its website. When the Department receives a
36 complaint via phone, mail, or online submission, it shall collect the following information from
37 the complainant:
38 (1) The name and contact information of the complainant.
39 (2) Whether the complainant is an association of unit owners or lot owners, or is
40 a unit owner or lot owner belonging to those associations.
41 (3) The name and contact information of the other party or parties to the dispute
42 giving rise to the complaint.
43 (4) The name, address, and contact information of the association management
44 company, if any, involved in the dispute.
45 (5) Details on whether the association member involved in the dispute (i) was
46 informed of the requirement of membership in the association as a condition
47 of unit or lot ownership and, if so informed, when and by whom; (ii) received
48 a copy of the governing documents of the association before obtaining title to
49 the property; (iii) was denied access to the association's governing documents;
50 and (iv) understood the rights and obligations of owners and the association
51 under the governing documents.
Page 18 House Bill 444-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (6) The nature of the complaint.
2 (7) The background information regarding the dispute, including whether the
3 member and association communicated about the dispute and whether all
4 other remedies available under the association's governing documents were
5 exhausted before the complaint was made.
6 (8) The complainant's understanding of the rights and obligations under the
7 association's governing documents as they relate to the dispute.
8 (9) The complainant's desired remedy regarding the dispute.
9 (b) Upon receiving the complaint, the Department shall provide a copy of the complaint
10 to the party complained against informing the party of the complaint made against it and allowing
11 for the party to respond.
12 (c) The Department shall publish the following information on its website:
13 (1) Information on the process to submit complaints pursuant to this section.
14 (2) Information about the laws and documents governing associations of unit
15 owners and lot owners in North Carolina.
16 (3) General information about roles, rights, and responsibilities of associations of
17 unit owners and lot owners, their members, and other related parties.
18 (4) Any other information the Department deems relevant to understanding the
19 rights and obligations of associations of unit owners and lot owners and
20 members of such associations.
21 (d) The Department is prohibited from promulgating regulations or issuing guidelines
22 concerning the administration, governance, or governing documents of associations of unit
23 owners or lot owners. The Department shall not serve as an arbiter in disputes between an
24 association of unit owners or lot owners and its members.
25 (e) By July 1 of each year, the Department shall submit a report to the House Standing
26 Committee on Commerce and Economic Development, the Senate Standing Committee on
27 Commerce and Insurance, and the Fiscal Research Division and shall also publish the report on
28 its website. The report shall include, at a minimum, a summary of all of the following:
29 (1) The total number of complaints received pursuant to this section.
30 (2) The number of those complaints submitted by unit owners or lot owners.
31 (3) The number of those complaints submitted by associations of unit owners or
32 lot owners.
33 (4) The number of complaints originating in each county of this State.
34 (5) The number of complaints that involved association management companies.
35 (6) The nature of the disputes reflected in the complaints, including:
36 a. Access to association records.
37 b. Access to executive board meetings.
38 c. Assessments.
39 d. Executive board transparency.
40 e. Fines.
41 f. Collections of delinquent accounts.
42 g. Liens.
43 h. Foreclosures.
44 i. Content of restrictive covenants.
45 j. Enforcement of restrictive covenants.
46 (7) A ranking of the top five disputes based on the nature of the dispute reflected
47 in the complaints.
48 (8) The number of responses to the complaints received by the Department.
49 The information summarized in the report must be categorized, filterable, and searchable.
50 The Department must redact any personal or private information from the report, such as names,
51 addresses, and telephone numbers of individuals. This redaction requirement does not apply to
House Bill 444-First Edition Page 19

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 information concerning a homeowners association or a homeowners association management
2 company."
3 SECTION 14.(b) This section becomes effective July 1, 2025.
4 SECTION 15. Sections 6 and 10 of this act become effective December 1, 2025, and
5 apply to claims of lien filed and instruments presented for registration on or after that date. Except
6 as otherwise provided, the remainder of this act is effective when it becomes law, and the
7 provisions in Sections 3 and 8 of this act relating to managing agent compensation apply to
8 contracts between an association and a managing agent entered into on or after that date.
